rty of the nearly one thousand ant species living in North America are true pests, we cringe when we see them marching across our kitchen floors. No longer! In this witty, accessible, and beautifully illustrated guide, Eleanor Spicer Rice, Alex Wild, and Rob Dunn metamorphose creepy-crawly revulsion into myrmecological wonder. Emerging from Dunn’s ambitious citizen science project Your Wild Life (an initiative based at North Carolina State University), Dr. Eleanor’s Book of Common Ants of Chicago provides an eye-opening entomological overview of the natural history of Chicago’s species most noted by project participants—and even offers tips on keeping ant farms in your home. Exploring species from the hobbit ant to the tiny trapjaw ant, and featuring contributions from E. O. Wilson and Field Museum ant scientist Corrie Moreau as well as Wild’s stunning photography, this guide will be a tremendous resource for teachers, students, and scientists alike. But more than this, it will transform the way Chicagoans perceive the environment around them by deepening their understanding of its littlest inhabitants, inspiring everyone to find their inner naturalist, get outside, and crawl across the dirt—magnifying glass in hand.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAntsxBehaviorzIllinoiszChicago. 0aAntszIllinoiszChicagoxBehavior. 0aAnts--Behavior--Illinois--Chicago. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  aentomology, entomologist, bugs, insects, illinois, regional, area, habitat, united states, usa, america, american, midwest, city, urban, academic, scholarly, biology, biodiversity, research, outdoors, nature, natural world, lifetime, lifespan, decomposer, pests, illustrated, guidebook, photographs, science, scientific, species, hobbit, trapjaw, naturalist.1 aDunn, Rob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 